<p> Writers, it&rsquo;s time to stop worrying and learn to love the command line. Your terminal is your friend. There&rsquo;s nothing to fear here. </p>
<p> In this little article, I will go through some fun and easy commands that will be helpful to the power-user writer. </p>
<p> Getting comfortable on the command line will open up a whole new world of possibilities for you and make it easier to get more done in less time. </p>
<p> <b>But remember, when you&rsquo;re talking command line, a &ldquo;folder&rdquo; is a &ldquo;directory.&rdquo;</b> </p>
<p> Cozy command line operation is different than clicking around a standard user interface. When using the terminal, it&rsquo;s a whole different approach. Instead of clicking on what you want, you are giving written instructions to the computer. You are, in essence, telling your computer to do things for you: </p>
<ul class="org-ul">
<li>&ldquo;Change this directory to&#x2026;&rdquo;</li>
<li>&ldquo;Tell me what&rsquo;s in this directory&rdquo;</li>
<li>&ldquo;Search my files for this pattern&#x2026;&rdquo;</li>
<li>&ldquo;Show me what is in this file&#x2026;&rdquo;</li>
</ul>
<p> The commands that follow will work for Mac and Linux users. So go ahead and fire up your terminal and let&rsquo;s get started. </p>
<div id="table-of-contents" role="doc-toc">
